  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "Without enough labeled data, it is harder to develop and test supervised machine learning (ML) and deep learning (DL) models.",
    "In addition, there are few comprehensive, publicly available sentiment lexicons designed for the health domain, and creating them requires significant resources (30).",
    "The rise of large language models (LLMs) offers some ways to reduce data scarcity problems.",
    "LLMs can work well in few-shot learning scenarios, which lowers the need for large labeled datasets (15, 36).",
    "Researchers are also exploring techniques like semisupervised learning with LLMs (68) and data augmentation (47) to overcome data limitations, often at lower costs than traditional methods (47)."
  ],
